<div id="review_2131243473" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2131243473" />
    <a title="Jeri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19203293-jeri"><img alt="Jeri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1365390184p2/19203293.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2131243473?book_show_action=true">Oct 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeri" href="/user/show/19203293-jeri">Jeri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/20508946-the-wide-game">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2131243473" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11256083988693326603">I read this book because it met the criteria for my monthly Book Club - something supernatural. I didn’t want to read vampires or Stephen King. I was actually looking at a Stephen King book on Amazon and this book was in the “other customers who looked at this book bought...”. I looked at this one and got it. <br/><br/>It started out great. People returning to the town of Harmony for a 10 year high school reunion. Then they talked about this high school annual Senior year tradition the Wide Game. Then Fla</span>
  <span id="freeText11256083988693326603" style="display:none">I read this book because it met the criteria for my monthly Book Club - something supernatural. I didn’t want to read vampires or Stephen King. I was actually looking at a Stephen King book on Amazon and this book was in the “other customers who looked at this book bought...”. I looked at this one and got it. <br /><br />It started out great. People returning to the town of Harmony for a 10 year high school reunion. Then they talked about this high school annual Senior year tradition the Wide Game. Then Flashback to high school! The book remained in the flashback time for most of the rest of the book. The author did a good job of character development for most of the characters. The story was about an ancient spirit “the Corn God” and horrible wicked things he caused to happen when you play the game. The Wide Game was never well explained, nor was the name explained. In short Seniors paid $5 to play. Whoever hiked through the miles of corn stalks to a quarry won all the money that had been paid, about $1,000 total. There were other rules about stealing things from other players that entitled them to share the prize, but again, not well explained. The author tried to build suspense by talking about things that happened in previous years. <br /><br />Everything starts to happen once darkness falls, of course. There were student cliques that played a part. Bullies. The football star. The head blonde cheerleader. The film geek and his girlfriend who were the main characters and a cast of others. The demon worked it’s evil by playing on the individual’s fears, hallucinations, scary crows, fog, confusion. There were deaths, murders, lots of running and getting separated. Horrible things that these kids would carry with them after they graduated. <br /><br />Then we are back at the Reunion. The two main characters were boyfriend/girlfriend. Smart, good looking, nice people. Then when they see one another the girl wants to get back together because they share a secret! The secret is completely out of character for either one. It has been forgotten totally but suddenly, there it is. Then there is a scene in a Catholic Church dealing with forgiveness and redemption. Then suddenly more hastily thrown in plot twists that don’t fit with anything. <br /><br />I think this is one of the worst, most disjointed and stupid books I ever read. I looked up the author and found he wrote two sequels to this book! Astounding! What this book doesn’t need is more! I understand this is the first book he wrote. It sucks. I truly hope he got better. Parts of the book were okay but most was absolutely terrible. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11256083988693326603" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


