<div id="review_2128574657" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2128574657" />
    <a title="Jill Franklin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56837703-jill-franklin"><img alt="Jill Franklin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509968952p2/56837703.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2128574657?book_show_action=true">Sep 19, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jill Franklin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jill Franklin" href="/user/show/56837703-jill-franklin">Jill Franklin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781937929183" href="/book/show/18160656-the-wide-game">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2128574657" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14351998680100593397">Horror is by far my fave genre and has been since childhood. When done well, it&apos;s challenging to say the least. It takes a special talent to skillfully bring to life plots and situations that are not suppose to exist. To bend reality, push the limitations without crossing over the line of cheesiness.<br/><br/>It goes without saying that King is the master at this, while it may become repetitious that the this is mentioned if this genre is so much as hinted at.......can you really talk about horror and not</span>
  <span id="freeText14351998680100593397" style="display:none">Horror is by far my fave genre and has been since childhood. When done well, it's challenging to say the least. It takes a special talent to skillfully bring to life plots and situations that are not suppose to exist. To bend reality, push the limitations without crossing over the line of cheesiness.<br /><br />It goes without saying that King is the master at this, while it may become repetitious that the this is mentioned if this genre is so much as hinted at.......can you really talk about horror and not mention King? <br /><br />I started reading King at 12 yrs old, have been reading horror since and there are only a handful of writers in this genre who do not simply pale in comparison. <br /><br />Michael West is in that elite handful. I thoroughly enjoyed all of the books in this series.<br /><br />The books do not piggyback one another , they are completely separate stories, independent of one another. <br /><br />So, while they can certainly be enjoyed as stand alone books, I would highly recommend reading all 3 to get the full picture of the supernatural haven that is Harmony Indiana.<br /><br />There is one character, Robby, that is at the heart of all 3 stories and others that consistently pop up and are mentioned throughout. <br /><br />This, along with Wests writing style and great story telling abilities, give you a sense of small town familiarity and bring to life, the town, community, the fear and the terror that takes place there.<br /><br />I look forward to more books by West :)</span>
  <a data-text-id="14351998680100593397" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


